# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: distributed-algorithms-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] A **Byzantine fault** is a condition of a system, particularly a distributed computing system, where a fault occurs such that different symptoms are presented to different observers, including imperfect information on whether a system component has failed.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is also known as a **Byzantine generals problem**, a **Byzantine agreement problem**, or a **Byzantine failure**.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is any fault presenting different symptoms to different observers.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine failure is the loss of a system service due to a Byzantine fault in systems that require consensus among multiple components.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The Byzantine allegory considers a number of generals who are attacking a fortress.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The generals must decide as a group whether to attack or retreat; some may prefer to attack, while others prefer to retreat.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The important thing is that all generals agree on a common decision, for a half-hearted attack by a few generals would become a rout, and would be worse than either a coordinated attack or a coordinated retreat.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated by the presence of treacherous generals who may not only cast a vote for a suboptimal strategy; they may do so selectively.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For instance, if nine generals are voting, four of whom support attacking while four others are in favor of retreat, the ninth general may send a vote of retreat to those generals in favor of retreat, and a vote of attack to the rest.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Those who received a retreat vote from the ninth general will retreat, while the rest will attack (which may not go well for the attackers).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated further by the generals being physically separated and having to send their votes via messengers who may fail to deliver votes or may forge false votes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Without message signing, Byzantine fault tolerance can only be achieved if the total number of generals is greater than three times the number of disloyal (faulty) generals.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] There can be a default vote value given to missing messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For example, missing messages can be given a "null" value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Further, if the agreement is that the null votes are in the majority, a pre-assigned default strategy can be used (e.g., retreat).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The typical mapping of this allegory onto computer systems is that the computers are the generals and their digital communication system links are the messengers.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Although the problem is formulated in the allegory as a decision-making and security problem, in electronics, it cannot be solved by cryptographic digital signatures alone, because failures such as incorrect voltages can propagate through the encryption process.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Thus, a faulty message could be sent such that some recipients detect the message as faulty (bad signature), others see it is having a good signature, and a third group also sees a good signature but with different message contents than the second group.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The problem of obtaining Byzantine consensus was conceived and formalized by Robert Shostak, who dubbed it the *interactive consistency* problem.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] This work was done in 1978 in the context of the NASA-sponsored SIFT project in the Computer Science Lab at SRI International.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] SIFT (for Software Implemented Fault Tolerance) was the brainchild of John Wensley, and was based on the idea of using multiple general-purpose computers that would communicate through pairwise messaging in order to reach a consensus, even if some of the computers were faulty.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] At the beginning of the project, it was not clear how many computers in total were needed to guarantee that a conspiracy of *n* faulty computers could not "thwart" the efforts of the correctly-operating ones to reach consensus.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Shostak showed that a minimum of 3*n+*1 are needed, and devised a two-round 3*n+1* messaging protocol that would work for *n*=1.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] His colleague Marshall Pease generalized the algorithm for any n > 0, proving that 3*n*+1 is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] These results, together with a later proof by Leslie Lamport of the sufficiency of 3*n* using digital signatures, were published in the seminal paper, *Reaching Agreement in the Presence of Faults.* The authors were awarded the 2005 Edsger W.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] To make the interactive consistency problem easier to understand, Lamport devised a colorful allegory in which a group of army generals formulate a plan for attacking a city.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] In its original version, the story cast the generals as commanders of the Albanian army.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The name was changed, eventually settling on "Byzantine", at the suggestion of Jack Goldberg to future-proof any potential offense-giving.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] This formulation of the problem, together with some additional results, were presented by the same authors in their 1982 paper, "The Byzantine Generals Problem".
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The objective of Byzantine fault tolerance is to be able to defend against failures of system components with or without symptoms that prevent other components of the system from reaching an agreement among themselves, where such an agreement is needed for the correct operation of the system.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The remaining operationally correct components of a Byzantine fault tolerant system will be able to continue providing the system's service as originally intended, assuming there are a sufficient number of accurately-operating components to maintain the service.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] When considering failure propagation only via errors, Byzantine failures are considered the most general and most difficult class of failures among the failure modes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The so-called fail-stop failure mode occupies the simplest end of the spectrum.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Thus, Byzantine failures can confuse failure detection systems, which makes fault tolerance difficult.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Despite the allegory, a Byzantine failure is not necessarily a security problem involving hostile human interference: it can arise purely from physical or software faults.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] This kind of fault tolerance does not encompass the correctness of the value itself; for example, an adversarial component that deliberately sends an incorrect value, but sends that same value consistently to all components, will not be caught in the Byzantine fault tolerance scheme.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Several early solutions were described by Lamport, Shostak, and Pease in 1982.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] There are many systems that claim BFT without meeting the above minimum requirements (e.g., blockchain).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Given that there is mathematical proof that this is impossible, these claims need to include a caveat that their definition of BFT strays from the original.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] That is, systems such as blockchain don't guarantee agreement.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] They use resource-intensive mechanisms that make disagreements impractical to maintain.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Several system architectures were designed c.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] 1980 that implemented Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] These include: Draper's FTMP, Honeywell's MMFCS, and SRI's SIFT.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] In 1999, Miguel Castro and Barbara Liskov introduced the "Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance" (PBFT) algorithm, which provides high-performance Byzantine state machine replication, processing thousands of requests per second with sub-millisecond increases in latency.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] After PBFT, several BFT protocols were introduced to improve its robustness and performance.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For instance, Q/U, HQ, Zyzzyva, and ABsTRACTs, addressed the performance and cost issues; whereas other protocols, like Aardvark and RBFT, addressed its robustness issues.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, Adapt tried to make use of existing BFT protocols, through switching between them in an adaptive way, to improve system robustness and performance as the underlying conditions change.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, BFT protocols were introduced that leverage trusted components to reduce the number of replicas, e.g., A2M-PBFT-EA and MinBFT.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Recent research addresses the scalability limits of traditional BFT implementations (which often incur $O(n^{2})$ communication complexity) by parallelizing consensus.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For example, the Cerberus protocol maps data to a large, fixed state space to couple consensus instances with specific transaction sets.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] This allows BFT processes to run independently in parallel, enabling linear scalability relative to the network size.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Several examples of Byzantine failures that have occurred are given in two equivalent journal papers.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] These and other examples are described on the NASA DASHlink web pages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance mechanisms use components that repeat an incoming message (or just its signature, which can be reduced to just a single bit of information if self-checking pairs are used for nodes) to other recipients of that incoming message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] All these mechanisms make the assumption that the act of repeating a message blocks the propagation of Byzantine symptoms.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For systems that have a high degree of safety or security criticality, these assumptions must be proven to be true to an acceptable level of fault coverage.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] When providing proof through testing, one difficulty is creating a sufficiently wide range of signals with Byzantine symptoms.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Such testing will likely require specialized fault injectors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Byzantine errors were observed infrequently and at irregular points during endurance testing for the newly constructed *Virginia*-class submarine, at least through 2005 (when the issues were publicly reported).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The Bitcoin network works in parallel to generate a blockchain with proof of work allowing the system to overcome Byzantine failures and reach a coherent global view of the system's state.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Some proof of stake blockchains also use BFT algorithms.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance is a crucial concept in blockchain technology, ensuring that a network can continue to function even when some nodes (participants) fail or act maliciously.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] This tolerance is necessary because blockchains are decentralized systems with no central authority, making it essential to achieve consensus among nodes, even if some try to disrupt the process.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably and as intended, especially in the presence of unexpected faults or adversarial conditions, is a complex challenge.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] By accepting that components may fail, and further that frontier AI models may deceive, Byzantine fault tolerance has been proposed as an approach towards AI safety.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Structuring AI systems as ensembles of AI artifacts or modules that check and balance each other leads to strong assurances that no single errant or deceptive component can easily steer the system into an unsafe state.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] , BFT-based systems are designed to tolerate up to one-third of faulty or malicious nodes without compromising the network's integrity.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] Instead of relying on a central authority, the network's security depends on the ability of honest nodes to outnumber and outmaneuver malicious ones.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] BFT is especially important in private or permissioned blockchains, where a limited number of known participants need to reach a consensus quickly and securely.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] These networks often use BFT protocols to enhance performance and security.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] For example, SAFEbus can achieve Byzantine fault tolerance within the order of a microsecond of added latency.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The SpaceX Dragon considers Byzantine fault tolerance in its design.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The Ares rocket avionics, now the Space Launch System (SLS), utilizes a triplex with an interstage of accomplish Byzantine resilience.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] The Orion spacecraft utilizes self-checking pairs to detect and mask Byzantine faults.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] In legislatures, civil societies, polls, statistical surveys, and so forth, systems that require a minimum supermajority threshold agreement greater than two-thirds are similar to consensus reflective of Byzantine Fault Tolerant -like characteristics.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/byzantine-fault] By contrast, systems that operate on the sub-supermajority basis of simple majorities or a minority government could be vulnerable to Byzantine fault -like behavior.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A fundamental problem in distributed computing and multi-agent systems is to achieve overall system reliability in the presence of a number of faulty processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] This often requires coordinating processes to reach **consensus**, or agree on some data value that is needed during computation.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Example applications of consensus include agreeing on what transactions to commit to a database in which order, state machine replication, and atomic broadcasts.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Real-world applications often requiring consensus include cloud computing, clock synchronization, PageRank, opinion formation, smart power grids, state estimation, control of UAVs (and multiple robots/agents in general), load balancing, blockchain, and others.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem requires agreement among a number of processes (or agents) on a single data value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Some of the processes (agents) may fail or be unreliable in other ways, so consensus protocols must be fault-tolerant or resilient.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The processes must put forth their candidate values, communicate with one another, and agree on a single consensus value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem is a fundamental problem in controlling multi-agent systems.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] One approach to generating consensus is for all processes (agents) to agree on a majority value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In this context, a majority requires at least one more than half of the available votes (where each process is given a vote).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] However, one or more faulty processes may skew the resultant outcome such that consensus may not be reached or may be reached incorrectly.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Protocols that solve consensus problems are designed to deal with a limited number of faulty processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] These protocols must satisfy several requirements to be useful.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For instance, a trivial protocol could have all processes output binary value 1.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] This is not useful; thus, the requirement is modified such that the production must depend on the input.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] That is, the output value of a consensus protocol must be the input value of some process.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Another requirement is that a process may decide upon an output value only once, and this decision is irrevocable.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A method is correct in an execution if it does not experience a failure.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A consensus protocol tolerating halting failures must satisfy the following properties.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Eventually, every correct process decides some value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Every correct process must agree on the same value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Variations on the definition of *integrity* may be appropriate, according to the application.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For example, a weaker type of integrity would be for the decision value to equal a value that some correct process proposed – not necessarily all of them.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] There is also a condition known as **validity** in the literature which refers to the property that a message sent by a process must be delivered.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A protocol that can correctly guarantee consensus amongst n processes of which at most t fail is said to be *t-resilient*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In evaluating the performance of consensus protocols two factors of interest are *running time* and *message complexity*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Running time is given in Big O notation in the number of rounds of message exchange as a function of some input parameters (typically the number of processes and/or the size of the input domain).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Message complexity refers to the amount of message traffic that is generated by the protocol.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Other factors may include memory usage and the size of messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Varying models of computation may define a "consensus problem".
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Some models may deal with fully connected graphs, while others may deal with rings and trees.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In some models message authentication is allowed, whereas in others processes are completely anonymous.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Shared memory models in which processes communicate by accessing objects in shared memory are also an important area of research.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In most models of communication protocol participants communicate through *authenticated channels.* This means that messages are not anonymous, and receivers know the source of every message they receive.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Some models assume a stronger, *transferable* form of authentication, where each *message* is signed by the sender, so that a receiver knows not just the immediate source of every message, but the participant that initially created the message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] This stronger type of authentication is achieved by digital signatures, and when this stronger form of authentication is available, protocols can tolerate a larger number of faults.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The two different authentication models are often called *oral communication* and *written communication* models.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In an oral communication model, the immediate source of information is known, whereas in stronger, written communication models, every step along the receiver learns not just the immediate source of the message, but the communication history of the message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the most traditional **single-value** consensus protocols such as Paxos, cooperating nodes agree on a single value such as an integer, which may be of variable size so as to encode useful metadata such as a transaction committed to a database.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A special case of the single-value consensus problem, called **binary consensus**, restricts the input, and hence the output domain, to a single binary digit {0,1}.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] While not highly useful by themselves, binary consensus protocols are often useful as building blocks in more general consensus protocols, especially for asynchronous consensus.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In **multi-valued** consensus protocols such as Multi-Paxos and Raft, the goal is to agree on not just a single value but a series of values over time, forming a progressively-growing history.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] While multi-valued consensus may be achieved naively by running multiple iterations of a single-valued consensus protocol in succession, many optimizations and other considerations such as reconfiguration support can make multi-valued consensus protocols more efficient in practice.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] There are two types of failures a process may undergo, a crash failure or a Byzantine failure.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A *crash failure* occurs when a process abruptly stops and does not resume.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] *Byzantine failure*s are failures in which absolutely no conditions are imposed.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For example, they may occur as a result of the malicious actions of an adversary.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A process that experiences a Byzantine failure may send contradictory or conflicting data to other processes, or it may sleep and then resume activity after a lengthy delay.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Of the two types of failures, Byzantine failures are far more disruptive.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Thus, a consensus protocol tolerating Byzantine failures must be resilient to every possible error that can occur.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] must have been proposed by some correct process.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem may be considered in the case of asynchronous or synchronous systems.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] While real world communications are often inherently asynchronous, it is more practical and often easier to model synchronous systems, given that asynchronous systems naturally involve more issues than synchronous ones.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In synchronous systems, it is assumed that all communications proceed in *rounds*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In one round, a process may send all the messages it requires, while receiving all messages from other processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In this manner, no message from one round may influence any messages sent within the same round.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous message-passing distributed system, in which at least one process may have a *crash failure*, it has been proven in the famous 1985 **FLP impossibility result** by Fischer, Lynch and Paterson that a deterministic algorithm for achieving consensus is impossible.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] This impossibility result derives from worst-case scheduling scenarios, which are unlikely to occur in practice except in adversarial situations such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In most normal situations, process scheduling has a degree of natural randomness.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In an asynchronous model, some forms of failures can be handled by a synchronous consensus protocol.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For instance, the loss of a communication link may be modeled as a process which has suffered a Byzantine failure.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Randomized consensus algorithms can circumvent the FLP impossibility result by achieving both safety and liveness with overwhelming probability, even under worst-case scheduling scenarios such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Consensus algorithms traditionally assume that the set of participating nodes is fixed and given at the outset: that is, that some prior (manual or automatic) configuration process has **permissioned** a particular known group of participants who can authenticate each other as members of the group.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the absence of such a well-defined, closed group with authenticated members, a Sybil attack against an open consensus group can defeat even a Byzantine consensus algorithm, simply by creating enough virtual participants to overwhelm the fault tolerance threshold.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A **permissionless** consensus protocol, in contrast, allows anyone in the network to join dynamically and participate without prior permission, but instead imposes a different form of artificial cost or barrier to entry to mitigate the Sybil attack threat.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Motivated in part by the high energy cost of this approach, subsequent permissionless consensus protocols have proposed or adopted other alternative participation rules for Sybil attack protection, such as proof of stake, proof of space, and proof of authority.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Three agreement problems of interest are as follows.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A collection of n processes, numbered from 0 to $n-1,$ communicate by sending messages to one another.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] 2. for any two correct processes, each process receives the same value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] It is also known as The General's Problem.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For *n* processes in a partially synchronous system (the system alternates between good and bad periods of synchrony), each process chooses a private value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] 2. all messages sent in a round by a correct process are received in the same round by all correct processes (consistency property).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] It can be shown that variations of these problems are equivalent in that the solution for a problem in one type of model may be the solution for another problem in another type of model.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For example, a solution to the Weak Byzantine General problem in a synchronous authenticated message passing model leads to a solution for Weak Interactive Consistency.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] An interactive consistency algorithm can solve the consensus problem by having each process choose the majority value in its consensus vector as its consensus value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] There is a t-resilient anonymous synchronous protocol which solves the Byzantine Generals problem, if ${\tfrac {t}{n}}<{\tfrac {1}{3}}$ and the Weak Byzantine Generals case where t is the number of failures and n is the number of processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] For systems with n processors, of which f are Byzantine, it has been shown that there exists no algorithm that solves the consensus problem for $n\leq 3f$ in the *oral-messages model*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The proof is constructed by first showing the impossibility for the three-node case $n=3$ and using this result to argue about partitions of processors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the *written-messages model* there are protocols that can tolerate $n=f+1$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous system there is no consensus solution that can tolerate one or more crash failures even when only requiring the non triviality property.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] This result is sometimes called the FLP impossibility proof named after the authors Michael J.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Fischer, Nancy Lynch, and Mike Paterson who were awarded a Dijkstra Prize for this significant work.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The FLP result has been mechanically verified to hold even under fairness assumptions.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] However, FLP does not state that consensus can never be reached: merely that under the model's assumptions, no algorithm can always reach consensus in bounded time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In practice it is highly unlikely to occur.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The Paxos consensus algorithm by Leslie Lamport, and variants of it such as Raft, are used pervasively in widely deployed distributed and cloud computing systems.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] These algorithms are typically synchronous, dependent on an elected leader to make progress, and tolerate only crashes and not Byzantine failures.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Other protocols, such as Cerberus, have been developed to apply Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus to sharded distributed ledgers and have been the subject of academic analysis.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] An example of a polynomial time binary consensus protocol that tolerates Byzantine failures is the Phase King algorithm by Garay and Berman.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The algorithm solves consensus in a synchronous message passing model with *n* processes and up to *f* failures, provided *n* > 4*f*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the phase king algorithm, there are *f* + 1 phases, with 2 rounds per phase.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Each process keeps track of its preferred output (initially equal to the process's own input value).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the first round of each phase each process broadcasts its own preferred value to all other processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] It then receives the values from all processes and determines which value is the majority value and its count.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In the second round of the phase, the process whose id matches the current phase number is designated the king of the phase.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The king broadcasts the majority value it observed in the first round and serves as a tie breaker.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Each process then updates its preferred value as follows.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] If the count of the majority value the process observed in the first round is greater than *n*/2 + *f*, the process changes its preference to that majority value; otherwise it uses the phase king's value.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] At the end of *f* + 1 phases the processes output their preferred values.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Google has implemented a distributed lock service library called Chubby.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Chubby maintains lock information in small files which are stored in a replicated database to achieve high availability in the face of failures.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The database is implemented on top of a fault-tolerant log layer which is based on the Paxos consensus algorithm.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] In this scheme, Chubby clients communicate with the Paxos *master* in order to access/update the replicated log; i.e., read/write to the files.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Many peer-to-peer online real-time strategy games use a modified lockstep protocol as a consensus protocol in order to manage game state between players in a game.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Each game action results in a game state delta broadcast to all other players in the game along with a hash of the total game state.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Each player validates the change by applying the delta to their own game state and comparing the game state hashes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Another well-known approach is called MSR-type algorithms which have been used widely in fields from computer science to control theory.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Bitcoin uses proof of work, a difficulty adjustment function and a reorganization function to achieve permissionless consensus in its open peer-to-peer network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] To extend bitcoin's blockchain or distributed ledger, *miners* attempt to solve a cryptographic puzzle, where probability of finding a solution is proportional to the computational effort expended in hashes per second.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The node that first solves such a puzzle has their proposed version of the next block of transactions added to the ledger and eventually accepted by all other nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] As any node in the network can attempt to solve the proof-of-work problem, a Sybil attack is infeasible in principle unless the attacker has over 50% of the computational resources of the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Ethereum, NEO, STRATIS, ...) use proof of stake, in which nodes compete to append blocks and earn associated rewards in proportion to *stake*, or existing cryptocurrency allocated and locked or *staked* for some time period.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] One advantage of a 'proof of stake' over a 'proof of work' system, is the high energy consumption demanded by the latter.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] As an example, bitcoin mining (2018) is estimated to consume non-renewable energy sources at an amount similar to the entire nations of Czech Republic or Jordan, while the total energy consumption of Ethereum, the largest proof of stake network, is just under that of 205 average US households.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Ripple, use a system of validating nodes to validate the ledger.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Step 4: the final round requires 80% agreement.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Other participation rules used in permissionless consensus protocols to impose barriers to entry and resist sybil attacks include proof of authority, proof of space, proof of burn, or proof of elapsed time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Proposed approaches to achieving one-per-person distribution of consensus power for proof of personhood include physical pseudonym parties, social networks, pseudonymized government-issued identities, and biometrics.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] To solve the consensus problem in a shared-memory system, concurrent objects must be introduced.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] A concurrent object, or shared object, is a data structure which helps concurrent processes communicate to reach an agreement.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Traditional implementations using critical sections face the risk of crashing if some process dies inside the critical section or sleeps for an intolerably long time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Researchers defined wait-freedom as the guarantee that the algorithm completes in a finite number of steps.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The **consensus number** of a concurrent object is defined to be the maximum number of processes in the system which can reach consensus by the given object in a wait-free implementation.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Objects with a consensus number of n can implement any object with a consensus number of n or lower, but cannot implement any objects with a higher consensus number.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] The consensus numbers form what is called Herlihy's hierarchy of synchronization objects.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] According to the hierarchy, read/write registers cannot solve consensus even in a 2-process system.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] Data structures like stacks and queues can only solve consensus between two processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/consensus-computer-science] However, some concurrent objects are universal (notated in the table with $\infty$ ), which means they can solve consensus among any number of processes and they can simulate any other objects through an operation sequence.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] In computer science, the **dining philosophers problem** is an example problem often used in concurrent algorithm design to illustrate synchronization issues and techniques for resolving them.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] It was originally formulated in 1965 by Edsger Dijkstra as a student exam exercise, presented in terms of computers competing for access to tape drive peripherals.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Soon after, Tony Hoare gave the problem its present form.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Five philosophers dine together at the same table.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Each philosopher has their own plate at the table.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] There is a fork between each pair of adjacent plates.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The dish served is a kind of spaghetti which has to be eaten with two forks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Each philosopher can only alternately think and eat.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Moreover, a philosopher can only eat their spaghetti when they have both a left and a right fork.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Thus, two forks will only be available when their two nearest neighbors are thinking, not eating.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] After an individual philosopher finishes eating, they will put down both forks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The problem is how to design a regimen (a concurrent algorithm) such that any philosopher will not starve; *i.e.*, each can forever continue to alternate between eating and thinking, assuming that no philosopher can know when others may want to eat or think (an issue of incomplete information).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The problem was designed to illustrate the challenges of avoiding deadlock, a system state in which no progress is possible.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] With these instructions, the situation may arise where each philosopher holds the fork to their left; in that situation, they will all be stuck forever, waiting for the other fork to be available: it is a deadlock.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Resource starvation, mutual exclusion, and livelock are other types of sequence and access problems.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] A solution must negate at least one of those four conditions.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] In practice, negating mutual exclusion or non-preemption somehow can give a valid solution, but most theoretical treatments assume that those assumptions are non-negotiable, instead attacking resource holding or circular waiting (often both).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Dijkstra's solution negates resource holding; the philosophers atomically pick up both forks or wait, never holding exactly one fork outside of a critical section.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] To accomplish this, Dijkstra's solution uses one mutex, one semaphore per philosopher, and one state variable per philosopher.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution is more complex than the resource hierarchy solution.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This is a C++20 version of Dijkstra's solution with changes by Andrew S.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The function test() and its use in take_forks() and put_forks() make the Dijkstra solution deadlock-free.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution negates circular waiting by assigning a partial order to the resources (the forks, in this case), and establishes the convention that all resources will be requested in order, and that no two resources unrelated by order will ever be used by a single unit of work at the same time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Here, the resources (forks) will be numbered 1 through 5, and each unit of work (philosopher) will always pick up the lower-numbered fork first, and then the higher-numbered fork, from among the two forks he plans to use.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The order in which each philosopher puts down the forks does not matter.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] In this case, if four of the five philosophers simultaneously pick up their lower-numbered forks, only the highest-numbered fork will remain on the table, so the fifth philosopher will not be able to pick up any fork.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Moreover, only one philosopher will have access to that highest-numbered fork, so he will be able to eat using two forks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This can intuitively be thought of as having one "left-handed" philosopher at the table, who – unlike all the other philosophers – takes his fork from the left first.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] While the resource hierarchy solution avoids deadlocks, it is not always practical, especially when the list of required resources is not completely known in advance.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] For example, if a unit of work holds resources 3 and 5 and then determines it needs resource 2, it must release 5, then 3, before acquiring 2, and then it must re-acquire 3 and 5 in that order.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Computer programs that access large numbers of database records would not run efficiently if they were required to release all higher-numbered records before accessing a new record, making the method impractical for that purpose.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The resource hierarchy solution is not *fair*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] If philosopher 1 is slow to take a fork, and if philosopher 2 is quick to think and pick their forks back up, then philosopher 1 will never get to pick up both forks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] A fair solution must guarantee that each philosopher will eventually eat, no matter how slowly that philosopher moves relative to the others.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The following source code is a C++11 implementation of the resource hierarchy solution for five philosophers.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The sleep_for() function simulates the time normally spent with business logic.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Another approach is to guarantee that a philosopher can only pick up both forks or none by introducing an arbitrator to replace circular waiting, e.g., a waiter.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] In order to pick up the forks, a philosopher must ask permission of the waiter.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The waiter gives permission to only one philosopher at a time until the philosopher has picked up both of his forks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The waiter can be implemented as a mutex.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] A solution presented by William Stallings is to allow a maximum of *n-1* philosophers to sit down at any time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The last philosopher would have to wait (for example, using a semaphore) for someone to finish dining before he "sits down" and requests access to any fork.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This negates circular wait, guaranteeing that at least one philosopher may always acquire both forks, allowing the system to make progress.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Misra proposed a different solution to the dining philosophers problem to allow for arbitrary agents (numbered *P*1, ..., *P**n*) to contend for an arbitrary number of resources, unlike Dijkstra's solution.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] It is also completely distributed and requires no central authority after initialization.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] However, it violates the requirement that "the philosophers do not speak to each other" (due to the request messages).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] When a philosopher wants to use a set of resources (*i.e.*, eat), the said philosopher must obtain the forks from his contending neighbors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] For all such forks that the philosopher does not have, he sends a request message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] When a philosopher with a fork receives a request message, he keeps the fork if it is clean, but gives it up when it is dirty.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] If the philosopher sends the fork over, he cleans the fork before doing so.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] After a philosopher is done eating, all his forks become dirty.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] If another philosopher had previously requested one of the forks, the philosopher who has just finished eating cleans the fork and sends it.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This solution also allows for a large degree of concurrency and will solve an arbitrarily large problem.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] The clean/dirty labels act as a way of giving preference to the most "starved" processes, and a disadvantage to processes that have just "eaten".
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] One could compare their solution to one where philosophers are not allowed to eat twice in a row without letting others use the forks in between.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Chandy and Misra's solution is more flexible than that, but has an element tending in that direction.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] In their analysis, they derive a system of preference levels from the distribution of the forks and their clean/dirty states.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] They show that this system may describe a directed acyclic graph, and if so, the operations in their protocol cannot turn that graph into a cyclic one.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] This guarantees that deadlock cannot occur by negating circular waiting.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] However, if the system is initialized to a perfectly symmetric state, like all philosophers holding their left side forks, then the graph is cyclic at the outset, and their solution cannot prevent a deadlock.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/dining-philosophers-problem] Initializing the system so that philosophers with lower IDs have dirty forks ensures the graph is initially acyclic.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] A **distributed algorithm** is an algorithm designed to run on computer hardware constructed from interconnected processors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are used in different application areas of distributed computing, such as telecommunications, scientific computing, distributed information processing, and real-time process control.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Standard problems solved by distributed algorithms include leader election, consensus, distributed search, spanning tree generation, mutual exclusion, and resource allocation.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are a sub-type of parallel algorithm, typically executed concurrently, with separate parts of the algorithm being run simultaneously on independent processors, and having limited information about what the other parts of the algorithm are doing.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] One of the major challenges in developing and implementing distributed algorithms is successfully coordinating the behavior of the independent parts of the algorithm in the face of processor failures and unreliable communications links.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] An atomic commit is an operation where a set of distinct changes is applied as a single operation.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] If the atomic commit succeeds, it means that all the changes have been applied.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] If there is a failure before the atomic commit can be completed, the "commit" is aborted and no changes will be applied.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Consensus algorithms try to solve the problem of a number of processes agreeing on a common decision.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] More precisely, a Consensus protocol must satisfy the four formal properties below.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Leader election is the process of designating a single process as the organizer of some task distributed among several computers (nodes).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Before the task is begun, all network nodes are unaware of which node will serve as the "leader," or coordinator, of the task.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] After a leader election algorithm has been run, however, each node throughout the network recognizes a particular, unique node as the task leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] Reliable broadcast is a communication primitive in distributed systems.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/distributed-algorithm] A reliable broadcast can have sequential, causal or total ordering.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In distributed computing, **leader election** is the process of designating a single process as the organizer of some task distributed among several computers (nodes).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Before the task has begun, all network nodes are either unaware which node will serve as the "leader" (or coordinator) of the task, or unable to communicate with the current coordinator.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "leader" state.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Leader election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Many other algorithms have been suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the leader election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The problem of leader election is for each processor eventually to decide whether it is a leader or not, subject to the constraint that exactly one processor decides that it is the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In every execution, exactly one processor becomes elected and the rest determine that they are not elected.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] **Uniqueness**: there is exactly one processor that considers itself as leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] **Agreement**: all other processors know who the leader is.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A ring network is a connected-graph topology in which each node is exactly connected to two other nodes, i.e., for a graph with n nodes, there are exactly n edges connecting the nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A ring is said to be anonymous if every processor is identical.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] More formally, the system has the same state machine for every processor.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] There is no deterministic algorithm to elect a leader in anonymous rings, even when the size of the network is known to the processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This is due to the fact that there is no possibility of breaking symmetry in an anonymous ring if all processes run at the same speed.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The state of processors after some steps only depends on the initial state of neighbouring nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] So, because their states are identical and execute the same procedures, in every round the same messages are sent by each processor.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Therefore, each processor state also changes identically and as a result if one processor is elected as a leader, so are all the others.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] For simplicity, here is a proof in anonymous synchronous rings.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Consider an anonymous ring R with size n>1.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Assume there exists an algorithm "A" to solve leader election in this anonymous ring R.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] of the admissible execution of A in R, all the processes have the same states.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The above lemma contradicts the fact that after some finite number of rounds in an execution of A, one process entered the elected state and other processes entered the non-elected state.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A common approach to solve the problem of leader election in anonymous rings is the use of probabilistic algorithms.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In such approaches, generally processors assume some identities based on a probabilistic function and communicate it to the rest of the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] At the end, through the application of an algorithm, a leader is selected (with high probability).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Since there is no algorithm for anonymous rings (proved above), the asynchronous rings would be considered as asynchronous non-anonymous rings.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In non-anonymous rings, each process has a unique $id$ , and they don't know the size of the ring.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Leader election in asynchronous rings can be solved by some algorithm with using $O(n^{2})$ messages or $O(n\log n)$ messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the $O(n^{2})$ algorithm, every process sends a message with its $id$ to the left edge.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Then waits until a message from the right edge.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is greater than its own $id$ , then forwards the message to the left edge; else ignore the message, and does nothing.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the $id$ in the message is equal to its own $id$ , then sends a message to the left announcing myself is elected.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Other processes forward the announcement to the left and turn themselves to non-elected.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] It is clear that the upper bound is $O(n^{2})$ for this algorithm.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the $O(n\log n)$ algorithm, it is running in phases.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] On the k th phase, a process will determine whether it is the winner among the left side $2^{k}$ and right side $2^{k}$ neighbors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If it is a winner, then the process can go to next phase.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In phase 0 , each process P needs to determine itself is a winner or not by sending a message with its $id$ to the left and right neighbors (neighbor do not forward the message).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The neighbor replies an $ACK$ only if the $id$ in the message is larger than the neighbor's $id$ , else replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If P receives two $ACK$ s, one from the left, one from the right, then P is the winner in phase 0 .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In phase k , the winners in phase $k-1$ need to send a message with its $id$ to the $2^{k}$ left and $2^{k}$ right neighbors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the neighbors in the path receive the $id$ in the message larger than their $id$ , then forward the message to the next neighbor, otherwise reply an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the $2^{k}$ th neighbor receives the $id$ larger than its $id$ , then sends back an $ACK$ , otherwise replies an $ACK_{fault}$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the process receives two $ACK$ s, then it is the winner in phase k .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the last phase, the final winner will receive its own $id$ in the message, then terminates and send termination message to the other processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the worst case, each phase there are at most ${\frac {n}{2^{k}+1}}$ winners, where k is the phase number.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] There are $\lceil \log(n-1)\rceil$ phases in total.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Each winner sends in the order of $2^{k}$ messages in each phase.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] So, the messages complexity is $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In Attiya and Welch's Distributed Computing book, they described a non-uniform algorithm using $O(n)$ messages in synchronous ring with known ring size n .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The algorithm is operating in phases, each phase has n rounds, each round is one time unit.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In phase 0 , if there is a process with $id=0$ , then process 0 sends termination message to the other processes (sending termination messages cost n rounds).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The algorithm will check if there is a phase number equals to a process $id$ , then does the same steps as phase 0 .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] At the end of the execution, the minimal $id$ will be elected as the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] It used exactly n messages and $n(minimum\_id+1)$ rounds.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Itai and Rodeh introduced an algorithm for a unidirectional ring with synchronized processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] They assume the size of the ring (number of nodes) is known to the processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] For a ring of size n, a≤n processors are active.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Each processor decides with probability of a^(-1) whether to become a candidate.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] At the end of each phase, each processor calculates the number of candidates c and if it is equal to 1, it becomes the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] To determine the value of c, each candidate sends a token (pebble) at the start of the phase which is passed around the ring, returning after exactly n time units to its sender.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Every processor determines c by counting the number of pebbles which passed through.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This algorithm achieves leader election with expected message complexity of O(nlogn).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A similar approach is also used in which a time-out mechanism is employed to detect deadlocks in the system.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] There are also algorithms for rings of special sizes such as prime size and odd size.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In typical approaches to leader election, the size of the ring is assumed to be known to the processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the case of anonymous rings, without using an external entity, it is not possible to elect a leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Even assuming an algorithm exists, the leader could not estimate the size of the ring. i.e. in any anonymous ring, there is a positive probability that an algorithm computes a wrong ring size.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] To overcome this problem, Fisher and Jiang used a so-called leader oracle Ω? that each processor can ask whether there is a unique leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] They show that from some point upward, it is guaranteed to return the same answer to all processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In one of the early works, Chang and Roberts proposed a uniform algorithm in which a processor with the highest ID is selected as the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Each processor sends its ID in a clockwise direction.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A processor receives a message and compares the ID with its own.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If the ID is bigger than the processor passes it through, otherwise it discards the message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The authors show that this algorithm uses $O(n^{2})$ messages in the worst case and $O(n\log n)$ in the average case.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Hirschberg and Sinclair improved this algorithm with $O(n\log n)$ message complexity by introducing a bidirectional message-passing scheme.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The mesh is another popular form of network topology, especially in parallel systems, redundant memory systems and interconnection networks.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In a mesh structure, nodes are either corner (only two neighbours), border (only three neighbours) or interior (with four neighbours).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The number of edges in a mesh of size a x b is m=2ab-a-b.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A typical algorithm to solve the leader election in an unoriented mesh is to only elect one of the four corner nodes as the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Since the corner nodes might not be aware of the state of other processes, the algorithm should first wake up the corner nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] *Election process*: the election in outer ring takes two stages at most with $6(a+b)-16$ messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] *Termination*: leader sends a terminating message to all nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The message complexity is at most $6(a+b)-16$ , and if the mesh is square-shaped, $O({\sqrt {n}})$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] An oriented mesh is a special case where port numbers are compass labels, i.e. north, south, east and west.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Leader election in an oriented mesh is trivial.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] "north" and "east" and make sure that node knows it is a leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A special case of mesh architecture is a torus which is a mesh with "wrap-around".
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In this structure, every node has exactly 4 connecting edges.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] One approach to elect a leader in such a structure is known as electoral stages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Similar to procedures in ring structures, this method in each stage eliminates potential candidates until eventually one candidate node is left.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This node becomes the leader and then notifies all other processes of termination.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This approach can be used to achieve a complexity of O(n).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] There also more practical approaches introduced for dealing with presence of faulty links in the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A Hypercube $H_{k}$ is a network consisting of $n=2^{k}$ nodes, each with degree of k and $O(n\log n)$ edges.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A similar electoral stages as before can be used to solve the problem of leader election.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In each stage two nodes (called duelists) compete and the winner is promoted to the next stage.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This means in each stage only half of the duelists enter the next stage.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This procedure continues until only one duelist is left, and it becomes the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Once selected, it notifies all other processes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This algorithm requires $O(n)$ messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the case of unoriented hypercubes, a similar approach can be used but with a higher message complexity of $O(n\log \log n)$ .
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Complete networks are structures in which all processes are connected to one another, i.e., the degree of each node is n-1, n being the size of the network.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] An optimal solution with O(n) message and space complexity is known.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Passive: the initial state of processes before start.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Candidate: the status of nodes after waking up.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The candidate nodes will be considered to become the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] There is an assumption that although a node does not know the total set of nodes in the system, it is required that in this arrangement every node knows the identifier of its single successor, which is called neighbor, and every node is known by another one.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] All processors initially start in a passive state until they are woken up.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Once the nodes are awake, they are candidates to become the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Based on a priority scheme, candidate nodes collaborate in the virtual ring.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] At some point, candidates become aware of the identity of candidates that precede them in the ring.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The higher priority candidates ask the lower ones about their predecessors.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The candidates with lower priority become dummies after replying to the candidates with higher priority.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Based on this scheme, the highest priority candidate eventually knows that all nodes in the system are dummies except itself, at which point it knows it is the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The above algorithm is not correct — it needs further improvement.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] As the name implies, these algorithms are designed to be used in any process network without prior knowledge of the network's topology or properties (such as size).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The Shout protocol builds a spanning tree on a generic graph and elects its root as leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The algorithm has a total cost linear in the edges cardinality.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This technique is similar to finding a Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) in which the root of the tree becomes the leader.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The idea is that individual nodes "merge" with each other to form bigger structures.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The result of this algorithm is a tree (a graph with no cycles) whose root is the leader of the entire system.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The cost of the mega-merger method is $O(m+n\log n)$ , where m is the number of edges and n is the number of nodes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Yo-yo (algorithm) is a minimum finding algorithm consisting of two parts: a preprocessing phase and a series of iterations.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the first phase or *setup*, each node exchanges its id with all its neighbours and based on the value it orients its incident edges.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] For instance, if node x has a smaller id than y, x orients towards y.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If a node has a smaller id than all its neighbours it becomes a **source**.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In contrast, a node with all inward edges (i.e., with id larger than all of its neighbours) is a **sink**.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Once all the edges are oriented, the *iteration* phase starts.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Each iteration is an electoral stage in which some candidates will be removed.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Each iteration has two phases: *YO-* and *–YO*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In this phase sources start the process to propagate to each sink the smallest values of the sources connected to that sink.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] An internal node waits to receive a value from all its in-neighbours.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] It calculates the minimum and sends it to out-neighbour.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A sink (a node with no outgoing edge) receives all the values and compute their minimum.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] An internal node sends YES to all in-neighbours from which it received the smallest value and NO to others.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If it receives only one NO, it sends NO to all.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] A source waits until it receives all votes.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If all YES, it survives and if not, it is no longer a candidate.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] When a node x sends NO to an in-neighbour y, the logical direction of that edge is reversed.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] When a node y receives NO from an out-neighbour, it flips the direction of that link.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] After the final stage, any source who receives a NO is no longer a source and becomes a sink.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] An additional stage, *pruning*, also is introduced to remove the nodes that are useless, i.e. their existence has no impact on the next iterations.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If, in the YO- phase the same value is received by a node from more than one in-neighbour, it will ask all but one to remove the link connecting them.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] This method has a total cost of O(m log n) messages.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Its real message complexity including pruning is an open research problem and is unknown.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In radio network protocols, leader election is often used as a first step to approach more advanced communication primitives, such as message gathering or broadcasts.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] The very nature of wireless networks induces collisions when adjacent nodes transmit at the same time; electing a leader allows to better coordinate this process.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] While the diameter *D* of a network is a natural lower bound for the time needed to elect a leader, upper and lower bounds for the leader election problem depend on the specific radio model studied.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In radio networks, the *n* nodes may in every round choose to either transmit or receive a message.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] If *no collision detection* is available, then a node cannot distinguish between silence or receiving more than one message at a time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Should *collision detection* be available, then a node may detect more than one incoming message at the same time, even though the messages itself cannot be decoded in that case.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] In the *beeping model*, nodes can only distinguish between silence or at least one message via carrier sensing.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/leader-election] Known runtimes for single-hop networks range from a constant (expected with collision detection) to *O(n log n)* rounds (deterministic and no collision detection).
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] A **logical clock** is a mechanism for capturing chronological and causal relationships in a distributed system.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] Often, distributed systems may have no physically synchronous global clock.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] In many applications (such as distributed GNU make), if two processes never interact, the lack of synchronization is unobservable and in these applications it is enough for the processes to agree on the event ordering (i.e., logical clock) rather than the wall-clock time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] The idea of logical clocks is due to Leslie Lamport, who introduced it in 1978 with his system of timestamps.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] In logical clock systems each process has two data structures: *logical local time* and *logical global time*.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] Logical local time is used by the process to mark its own events, and logical global time is the local information about global time.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] A special protocol is used to update logical local time after each local event, and logical global time when processes exchange data.
[src:distributed-algorithms-theory/logical-clock] Logical clocks are useful in computation analysis, distributed algorithm design, individual event tracking, and exploring computational progress.
